{"title_page": "Late Night Conversations", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Late Night Conversations\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Forecast]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = May 17, 2005\n| recorded   = Nov, 2004 <ref name=\"LinerNotes\">''Late Night Conversations'' ([[liner notes]]). [[The Forecast]]. [[Victory Records]]. 2005.</ref>\n| venue      = [[Presto! Recording Studios]]<ref name=\"LinerNotes\"/>\n| studio     = Studio B<ref name=\"LinerNotes\"/>\n| genre      = [[Indie rock]], [[emo]]\n| length     = 38:18\n| label      = [[Victory Records]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[A. J. Mogis]]|[[The Forecast]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Relationships Ruin Friendships]]\n| prev_year  = 2005\n| next_title = [[In the Shadow of Two Gunmen (album)|In the Shadow of Two Gunmen]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n}}\n\n'''''Late Night Conversations''''' is the first album by [[Illinois]] [[indie rock]] band [[The Forecast]]. It was released on May 17, 2005.\n\n==Track listing==\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = [[Dustin Addis]], [[Shannon Burns]], [[Matt Webb]], [[Tony Peck]], except where noted\n| total_length    = 38:18\n| title1          = Seating Subject to Availability\n| length1         = 3:54\n| writer1         = \n| title2          = These Lights\n| length2         = 2:49\n| writer2         = Guest vocals by Gared O'Donnell and Matt Bellinger of [[Planes Mistaken For Stars]]<ref name=\"LinerNotes\"/>\n| title3          = Helping Hands\n| length3         = 2:34\n| writer3         = \n| title4          = Fade In, Fade Out\n| length4         = 2:29\n| writer4         = \n| title5          = Whiskey's Dead You're Next\n| length5         = 3:50\n| writer5         = Guitar Noise by [[A. J. Mogis]]<ref name=\"LinerNotes\"/>\n| title6          = Late Night Conversations\n| length6         = 4:09\n| writer6         = \n| title7          = APR\n| length7         = 3:32\n| writer7         = \n| title8          = Exorcise Demons\n| length8         = 6:20\n| writer8         = \n| title9          = Sleep Tight Tonight\n| length9         = 6:03\n| writer9         = \n| title10         = Losing Signal\n| length10        = 2:38\n| writer10        = \n}}\n\n==References To Other Media==\nIn the [[Liner Notes]], the Lyrics \"hangmen, heroes, lovers, and pawns\" from \"These Lights\" are noted as \"inspired by Tim Mead\" <ref name=\"LinerNotes\"/>. This is likely a direct reference to the same lyrics in \"Holy Flower of the North Star\", from the Album [[Out of a Center Which Is Neither Dead nor Alive]] by the Chicago-based [[post-metal]] band [[Minsk (band)|Minsk]], In which [[Minsk (band)#Members|Timothy Mead]] is a member.{{citation Needed}}\n\n\n==Appearances In [[Video Games]]==\n\n* The single \"These Lights\" was featured in [[MVP 06 NCAA Baseball]] for the [[Playstation 2]]\n* The singles \"Seating Subject to Availability\", \"These Lights\", \"Fade In, Fade Out\", \"late Night Conversations\" are featured in [[Amped 3]] for the [[Xbox 360]]\n\n[[Category:2005 albums]]\n[[Category:The Forecast albums]]\n\n\n{{2000s-alt-rock-album-stub}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Late Night Conversations\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Forecast]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = May 17, 2005\n| recorded   = Nov, 2004 <ref name=\"LinerNotes\">''Late Night Conversations'' ([[liner notes]]). [[The Forecast]]. [[Victory Records]]. 2005.</ref>\n| venue      = [[Presto! Recording Studios]]<ref name=\"LinerNotes\"/>\n| studio     = Studio B<ref name=\"LinerNotes\"/>\n| genre      = [[Indie rock]], [[emo]]\n| length     = 38:18\n| label      = [[Victory Records]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[A. J. Mogis]]|[[The Forecast]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Relationships Ruin Friendships]]\n| prev_year  = 2005\n| next_title = [[In the Shadow of Two Gunmen (album)|In the Shadow of Two Gunmen]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n}}\n\n'''''Late Night Conversations''''' is the first album by [[Illinois]] [[indie rock]] band [[The Forecast]]. It was released on May 17, 2005.\n\n==Track listing==\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = [[Dustin Addis]], [[Shannon Burns]], [[Matt Webb]], [[Tony Peck]], except where noted\n| total_length    = 38:18\n| title1          = Seating Subject to Availability\n| length1         = 3:54\n| writer1         = \n| title2          = These Lights\n| length2         = 2:49\n| writer2         = Guest vocals by Gared O'Donnell and Matt Bellinger of [[Planes Mistaken For Stars]]<ref name=\"LinerNotes\"/>\n| title3          = Helping Hands\n| length3         = 2:34\n| writer3         = \n| title4          = Fade In, Fade Out\n| length4         = 2:29\n| writer4         = \n| title5          = Whiskey's Dead You're Next\n| length5         = 3:50\n| writer5         = Guitar Noise by [[A. J. Mogis]]<ref name=\"LinerNotes\"/>\n| title6          = Late Night Conversations\n| length6         = 4:09\n| writer6         = \n| title7          = APR\n| length7         = 3:32\n| writer7         = \n| title8          = Exorcise Demons\n| length8         = 6:20\n| writer8         = \n| title9          = Sleep Tight Tonight\n| length9         = 6:03\n| writer9         = \n| title10         = Losing Signal\n| length10        = 2:38\n| writer10        = \n}}\n\n==References To Other Media==\nIn the [[Liner Notes]], the Lyrics \"hangmen, heroes, lovers, and pawns\" from \"These Lights\" are noted as \"inspired by Tim Mead\" <ref name=\"LinerNotes\"/>. This is likely a direct reference to the same lyrics in \"Holy Flower of the North Star\", from the Album, [[Out of a Center Which Is Neither Dead nor Alive]], by the Chicago-based [[post-metal]] band, [[Minsk (band)|Minsk]]. In which [[Minsk (band)#Members|Timothy Mead]] is a member.{{citation Needed}}\n\n\n==Appearances In [[Video Games]]==\n\n* The single \"These Lights\" was featured in [[MVP 06 NCAA Baseball]] for the [